<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2005D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Find the speed of a particle with the given position function
<me>
\vr(t) = 5 \sqrt{2}\,t\,\hi + e^{5t}\,\hj - e^{-5t}\,\hk
</me>
Select the correct answer:
<ol label="a">
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = \big(e^{5t} + e^{-5t}\big)</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = \sqrt{10 + 5e^{t} + 5e^{-t}}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = \sqrt{10 + e^{10t} + e^{-10t}}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = 5\big(e^{5t} + e^{-5t}\big)</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = 5\big(e^t + e^{-t}\big)</m>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Just compute <m>|\vv(t)|</m>. Note that <m>\big(e^{at}+e^{-at}\big)^2
=e^{2at} + 2 + e^{-2at}</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(d)
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We have
<me>
\vv(t) = \vr'(t)
      = 5 \sqrt{2}\,\hi + 5e^{5t}\,\hj +5 e^{-5t}\,\hk
</me>
and hence
<me>
|\vv(t)| = |\vr'(t)|
         = 5 \big|\sqrt{2}\,\hi + e^{5t}\,\hj + e^{-5t}\,\hk\big|
         = 5\sqrt{2+ e^{10t}+ e^{-10t}}
</me>
Since <m>2+ e^{10t}+ e^{-10t} = \big(e^{5t}+e^{-5t}\big)^2</m>, that's (d).
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the velocity, speed and acceleration at time <m>t</m> of
the particle whose position is <m>\vr(t)</m>. Describe the path of the particle.
<ol label="a">
<li>
<m>\vr(t)= a \cos t\,\hi + a\sin t\,\hj + ct\,\hk</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>\vr(t)= a \cos t\sin t\,\hi + a\sin^2 t\,\hj + a\cos t\,\hk</m>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
To figure out what the curves look like, first detemine what curve
<m>\big(x(t),y(t)\big)</m> traces out. For part (b) this will be easier
if trig identities are first used to express <m>x(t)</m> and <m>y(t)</m> in terms of
<m>\sin(2t)</m> and <m>\cos(2t)</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a)
<md>
<mrow>
\vv(t)&amp;= -a \sin t\,\hi+a\cos t\,\hj+c\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{t}(t)&amp;= \sqrt{a^2+c^2}
</mrow><mrow>
\va(t)&amp;= -a \cos t\,\hi-a\sin t\,\hj
</mrow>
</md>
The path is a helix with radius <m>a</m> and with each turn having height <m>2\pi c</m>.
</p>

<p>(b)
<md>
<mrow>
\vv(t)&amp;= a \cos 2t\,\hi +a\sin 2t\,\hj-a\sin t\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{t}(t)&amp;= a\sqrt{1+\sin^2t}
</mrow><mrow>
\va(t)&amp;= -2a \sin 2t\,\hi +2a\cos 2t\,\hj-a\cos t\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
The <m>(x,y)</m> coordinates go around a circle of radius <m>\frac{a}{2}</m> and
centre <m>\big(0,\frac{a}{2}\big)</m> counterclockwise. At the same time the <m>z</m> coordinate oscillates over the interval between <m>1</m> and <m>-1</m> half as fast.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) By definition,
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t)&amp;= a \cos t\,\hi+a\sin t\,\hj+ct\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vv(t)=\vr'(t)&amp;= -a \sin t\,\hi+a\cos t\,\hj+c\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{t}(t)=|\vv(t)|&amp;= \sqrt{a^2+c^2}
</mrow><mrow>
\va(t)=\vr'(t)&amp;= -a \cos t\,\hi-a\sin t\,\hj
</mrow>
</md>
The <m>(x,y)= a(\cos t,\sin t)</m> coordinates go
     around a circle of radius <m>a</m> and centre <m>(0,0)</m> counterclockwise.
     One circle is completed for each increase of <m>t</m> by <m>2\pi</m>.
     At the same time, the <m>z</m> coordinate increases at a constant rate.
     Each time the <m>(x,y)</m> coordinates complete one circle, the <m>z</m>
     coordinate increases by <m>2 \pi c</m>.
The path is a helix with radius <m>a</m> and with each turn having height <m>2\pi c</m>.
</p>

<p>(b) By definition,
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t)&amp;= a \cos t\sin t\,\hi +a\sin^2 t\,\hj+a\cos t\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= \frac{a}{2} \sin 2t\,\hi+a\frac{1-\cos 2t}{2}\,\hj+a\cos t\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vv(t)=\vr'(t)&amp;= a \cos 2t\,\hi +a\sin 2t\,\hj-a\sin t\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{t}(t)=|\vv(t)|&amp;= a\sqrt{1+\sin^2t}
</mrow><mrow>
\va(t)=\vr'(t)&amp;= -2a \sin 2t\,\hi +2a\cos 2t\,\hj-a\cos t\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
The <m>(x,y)</m> coordinates go around a circle of radius <m>\frac{a}{2}</m> and
centre <m>\big(0,\frac{a}{2}\big)</m> counterclockwise. At the same time the <m>z</m> coordinate oscillates over the interval between <m>1</m> and <m>-1</m> half as fast.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2013D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p><ol label="a">
<li>
Let
<me>
\vr(t) = \left(t^2 , 3, \tfrac{1}{3} t^3 \right)
</me>
Find the unit tangent vector to this parametrized curve at <m>t = 1</m>,
pointing in the direction of increasing <m>t</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the arc length of the curve from (a) between the points <m>(0, 3, 0)</m>
and <m>(1, 3, -\frac{1}{3})</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Review Lemma <xref ref="lem_CVtanArclen"/> in the CLP-3 text.
The arc length should be positive.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\hat\vT(1) = \frac{(2,0,1)}{\sqrt{5}}</m>
</p><p>
(b) <m>\frac{1}{3}\big[5^{3/2}-8\big]</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a)
Since <m>\vr'(t) = (2t,0,t^2)</m>, the specified unit tangent at <m>t=1</m> is
<me>
\hat\vT(1) = \frac{(2,0,1)}{\sqrt{5}}
</me>
</p>

<p>(b)
We are to find the arc length between <m>\vr(0)</m> and <m>\vr(-1)</m>.
As <m>\diff{s}{t}=\sqrt{4t^2+t^4}</m>, the
<md>
<mrow>
\text{arc length} &amp;= \int_{-1}^0 \sqrt{4t^2+t^4}\ \dee{t}
</mrow>
</md>
The integrand is even, so
<md>
<mrow>
\text{arc length} &amp;= \int_0^1 \sqrt{4t^2+t^4}\ \dee{t}
=\int_0^1 t\sqrt{4+t^2}\ \dee{t}
=\Big[\tfrac{1}{3}{(4+t^2)}^{3/2}\Big]_0^1
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\tfrac{1}{3}\big[5^{3/2}-8\big]
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="prob_s1_1_lemma113">
<statement><p>
Using Lemma<nbsp/><xref ref="lem_CVtanArclen"/> in the CLP-3 text, find the arclength of <m>\vr(t)=\left(t,\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}t^2,t^3\right)</m> from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=1</m>.
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
From Lemma<nbsp/><xref ref="lem_CVtanArclen"/> in the CLP-3 text,
we know the arclength from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=1</m> will be
<me>
\int_{0}^1\left| \diff{\vr}{t}(t)\right|\dee t</me>
</p>

<p>The notation looks a little confusing at first, but we can break it down piece by piece: <m>\diff{\vr}{t}(t)</m> is a vector, whose components are functions of <m>t</m>. If we take its magnitude, we'll get one big function of <m>t</m>. That function is what we integrate. Before integrating it, however, we should simplify as much as possible.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
2
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
By Lemma<nbsp/><xref ref="lem_CVtanArclen"/> in the CLP-3 text,
the arclength of <m>\vr(t)</m> from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=1</m> is
<m>\int_{0}^1\left| \diff{\vr}{t}(t)\right|\dee t</m>. We'll calculate this in a few pieces to make the steps clearer.
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t)&amp;=\left(t,\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}t^2,t^3\right)
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{\vr}{t}(t)&amp;=\left(1,\sqrt{6}t,3t^2\right)
</mrow><mrow>
\left|\diff{\vr}{t}(t)\right|&amp;=\sqrt{1^2+(\sqrt{6}t)^2+(3t^2)^2}=\sqrt{1+6t^2+9t^4}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\sqrt{(3t^2+1)^2}=3t^2+1
</mrow><mrow>
\int_{0}^1\left| \diff{\vr}{t}(t)\right|\dee t&amp;=\int_0^1\left(3t^2+1 \right)\dee t=2
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
A particle's position at time <m>t</m> is given by <m>\vr(t)=(t+\sin t, \cos t)</m>
<fn>The particle traces out a cycloid--see Question<nbsp/><xref ref="prob_s1_1_cycloid"/></fn>
. What is the magnitude of the acceleration of the particle at time <m>t</m>?
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
<m>\vr(t)</m> is the position of the particle, so its acceleration is <m>r'(t)</m>.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
1
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
Since <m>\vr(t)</m> is the position of the particle,  its acceleration is <m>r'(t)</m>.
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t)&amp;=(t+\sin t, \cos t)
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(t)&amp;=(1+\cos t,-\sin t)
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(t)&amp;=(-\sin t,-\cos t)
</mrow><mrow>
|\vr'(t)|&amp;=\sqrt{\sin^2t+\cos^2t}=1
</mrow>
</md>
The magnitude of acceleration is constant, but its <em>direction</em> is changing, since <m>\vr'(t)</m> is a vector with changing direction.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2011D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
A curve in <m>\bbbr^3</m> is given by the vector equation
<m>\vr(t) = \left(2t \cos t, 2t \sin t,\frac{t^3}{3}\right)</m>
</p>

<p><ol label="a">
<li>
Find the length of the curve between <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 2</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the parametric equations of the tangent line to the curve at <m>t = \pi</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Review ยง<xref ref="sec_lines_3d"/> and  Lemma <xref ref="lem_CVtanArclen"/>
in the CLP-3 text.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\frac{20}{3}</m>
</p><p>
(b) <m>x(t) = -2\pi -2t,\
     y(t) =  -2\pi t,\
     z(t) = \frac{\pi^3}{3} + \pi^2 t</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a) The speed is
<md>
<mrow>
\diff{s}{t}(t)
=\big|\vr'(t)\big| &amp; = \left|\left(2\cos t - 2t\sin t\,,\,
                                  2\sin t + 2t \cos t\,,\,
                                  t^2\right)\right|
</mrow><mrow>
                  &amp;=\sqrt{\big(2\cos t - 2t\sin t\big)^2
                         +\big(2\sin t + 2t \cos t\big)^2
                         +t^4}
</mrow><mrow>
                 &amp;= \sqrt{4+ 4t^2 +t^4}
</mrow><mrow>
                 &amp;= 2+t^2
</mrow>
</md>
so the length of the curve is
<md>
<mrow>
\text{length }
&amp;=\int_0^2 \diff{s}{t}\,\dee{t}
  =\int_0^2 (2+t^2)\,\dee{t}
  = \left[2t +\frac{t^3}{3}\right]_0^2
  =\frac{20}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b)
A tangent vector to the curve at
<m>\vr(\pi)=\big(-2\pi\,,\, 0\,,\, \frac{\pi^3}{3}\big)</m> is
<me>
\vr'(\pi) = \left(2\cos\pi - 2\pi\sin\pi\,,\,
                                  2\sin\pi + 2\pi \cos\pi\,,\,
                                  \pi^2\right)
 = (-2\,,\,-2\pi\,,\,\pi^2)
</me>
So parametric equations for the tangent line at <m>\vr(\pi)</m> are
<md>
<mrow>
x(t) &amp;= -2\pi -2t
</mrow><mrow>
y(t) &amp;=  -2\pi t
</mrow><mrow>
z(t) &amp;= \frac{\pi^3}{3} + \pi^2 t
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2010D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vr(t) = \big(3 \cos t, 3 \sin t, 4t\big)</m> be the position vector
of a particle as a function of time <m>t \ge 0</m>.
<ol label="a">
<li>
Find the velocity of the particle as a function of time <m>t</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the arclength of its path between <m>t = 1</m> and <m>t = 2</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Review Lemma <xref ref="lem_CVtanArclen"/> in the CLP-3 text.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\vr'(t) = \big(-3 \sin t, 3 \cos t, 4\big)</m>
</p><p>
(b) 5
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a) As <m>\vr(t) = \big(3 \cos t, 3 \sin t, 4t\big)</m>,
the velocity of the particle is
<me>
\vr'(t) = \big(-3 \sin t, 3 \cos t, 4\big)
</me>
</p>

<p> (b) As <m>\diff{s}{t}</m>, the rate of change of arc length per unit time,
is
<me>
\diff{s}{t}(t) = |\vr'(t)| = \big|\big(-3 \sin t, 3 \cos t, 4\big)\big|
  =5
</me>
the arclength of its path between <m>t = 1</m> and <m>t = 2</m> is
<me>
\int_1^2\dee{t}\ \diff{s}{t}(t)
=\int_1^2\dee{t}\ 5
=5
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2007A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
	Consider the curve
	<me>
	\vr(t) = \frac{1}{3}\cos^3 t\,\hi +\frac{1}{3} \sin^3 t\,\hj + \sin^3 t\,\hk
	</me>
	<ol label="a">
<li>
		Compute the arc length of the curve from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
</li>
<li>
		Compute the arc length of the curve from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \pi</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
	If you got the answer <m>0</m> in part (b), you dropped some absolute value signs.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
	(a) <m>\frac{1}{27}\big(10\sqrt{10}-1\big)</m>
</p><p>
	(b) <m>\frac{2}{27}\big(10\sqrt{10}-1\big)</m>
</p></answer>

<solution>
<p> (a)
As
<md>
<mrow>
   \vr'(t) &amp; = -\sin t\cos^2 t\,\hi + \sin^2 t\cos t\,\hi + 3\sin^2 t\cos t\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;= \sin t\cos t\big(-\cos t\,\hi +\sin t\,\hj +3\sin t\,\hk\big)
</mrow><mrow>
	\diff{s}{t}(t) &amp; = |\sin t\cos t|\sqrt{\cos^2 t + \sin ^2 t + 9\sin^2 t}
	= |\sin t\cos t|\sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}
	</mrow>
</md>
the arclength from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \frac{\pi}{2}</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
	\int_0^{\pi/2} \diff{s}{t}(t)\,\dee{t}
	&amp;=\int_0^{\pi/2} \sin t\cos t \sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;=\frac{1}{18}\int_1^{10} \sqrt{u}\ \dee{u} 
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;\hskip0.5in\text{with } u = 1+ 9\sin^2 t,\ \dee{u}  = 18\sin t\cos t\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;=\frac{1}{18}\Big[\frac{2}{3}u^{3/2}\Big]_1^{10}
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;=\frac{1}{27}\big(10\sqrt{10}-1\big)
	</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>	(b) The arclength from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \pi</m> is
	<md>
<mrow>
	\int_0^{\pi} \diff{s}{t}(t)\,\dee{t}
	&amp;=\int_0^{\pi} |\sin t\cos t| \sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip0.5in\text{Don't forget the absolute value signs!}
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;=2\int_0^{\pi/2} |\sin t\cos t| \sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
        &amp;= 2\int_0^{\pi/2} \sin t\cos t \sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}\,\dee{t}
	</mrow>
</md>
	since the integrand is invariant under <m>t\rightarrow\pi-t</m>. So the arc length
	from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \pi</m> is just twice the arc length from part (a), namely <m>\frac{2}{27}\big(10\sqrt{10}-1\big)</m>.
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2017D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vr(t)=\big(\frac{1}{3}t^3,\frac{1}{2}t^2,\frac{1}{2}t\big)</m>,
<m>t\ge 0</m>. Compute <m>s(t</m>), the arclength of the curve at time
<m>t</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>s(t)=\frac{t^3}{3} +\frac{t}{2}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Since
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t)&amp;= \frac{t^3}{3}\,\hi + \frac{t^2}{2}\,\hj +  \frac{t}{2}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(t)&amp;= t^2\,\hi + t\,\hj + \frac{1}{2}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{t}(t)=|\vr'(t)|&amp;=\sqrt{t^4+t^2+\frac{1}{4}}
=\sqrt{\Big(t^2+\frac{1}{2}\Big)^2}=t^2+\frac{1}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
the length of the curve is
<md>
<mrow>
s(t)=\int_0^t \diff{s}{t}(u)\,\dee{u}
=\int_0^t \Big(u^2+\frac{1}{2}\Big)\,\dee{u}
=\frac{t^3}{3} +\frac{t}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2011A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Find the arc length of the curve
<m>\vr(t) = \big(t^m\,,\, t^m\,,\, t^{3m/2}\big)</m> for <m>0 \le a \le t \le b</m>,
and where <m>m  \gt  0</m>.
Express your result in terms of <m>m</m>, <m>a</m>, and <m>b</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The integral you get can be evaluated with
a simple substitution. You may want to factor the integrand first.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{8}{27}\Big[\Big(2 + \frac{9}{4}b^m\Big)^{3/2}
                   -\Big(2 + \frac{9}{4}a^m\Big)^{3/2}\Big]</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Since
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t) &amp; = t^m\,\hi + t^m\,\hj + t^{3m/2}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(t) &amp;= mt^{m-1}\,\hi + mt^{m-1}\,\hj +\frac{3m}{2}t^{3m/2-1}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{t} = |\vr'(t)| &amp; = \sqrt{ 2m^2 t^{2m-2} +\frac{9m^2}{4} t^{3m-2} }
= mt^{m-1}\sqrt{2 + \frac{9}{4}t^m }
</mrow>
</md>
the arc length is
<md>
<mrow>
\int_a^b \diff{s}{t}(t)\,\dee{t}
&amp;=\int_a^b mt^{m-1}\sqrt{2 + \frac{9}{4}t^m }\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{4}{9}\int_{2 + \frac{9}{4}a^m}^{2 + \frac{9}{4}b^m}\sqrt{u}\,\dee{u}
\qquad\text{with } u = 2 + \frac{9}{4}t^m,\ \dee{u} = \frac{9m}{4}t^{m-1}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{4}{9}\Big[\frac{2}{3}u^{3/2}\Big]_{2 + \frac{9}{4}a^m}
                                         ^{2 + \frac{9}{4}b^m}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{8}{27}\Big[\Big(2 + \frac{9}{4}b^m\Big)^{3/2}
                   -\Big(2 + \frac{9}{4}a^m\Big)^{3/2}\Big]
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
If a particle has constant mass <m>m</m>, position <m>\vr</m>, and is moving with velocity <m>\vv</m>, then its angular momentum is <m>\vL=m(\vr\times\vv)</m>.
</p>

<p>For a particle with mass <m>m=1</m> and position function <m>\vr=(\sin t, \cos t, t)</m>, find <m>\left|\diff{\vL}{t} \right|</m>.
</p>

</statement>
<hint><p>
Given the position of a particle, you can find its velocity.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
<m>|t|</m>
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
Given the position of the particle, we can find its velocity:
<me>
\vv(t)=\vr'(t)=(\cos t, -\sin t , 1)</me>
</p>

<p>Applying the given formula,
<me>
\vL(t)=\vr \times \vv=(\sin t , \cos t , t) \times (\cos t, -\sin t , 1).</me>
</p>

<p><ul>
<li>[<alert>Solution 1:</alert>]
We can first compute the cross product, then differentiate:
<md>
<mrow>
\vL(t)&amp; = (\cos t + t\sin t)\hi + (t\cos t - \sin t)\hj-\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vL'(t)&amp;=t\cos t\,\hi -t\sin t\, \hj
</mrow><mrow>
|\vL'(t)|&amp;=\sqrt{t^2(\sin^2 t + \cos^2 t)}=\sqrt{t^2}=|t|
</mrow>
</md>
</li>
<li>[<alert>Solution 2:</alert>]
Using the product rule:
<md>
<mrow>
\vL'(t)&amp;=\vr'(t)\times \vv(t) + \vr(t) \times \vv'(t)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\underbrace{\vr'(t)\times \vr'(t)}_{0} + \vr(t) \times \vv'(t)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= (\sin t ,\cos t,t)\times(-\sin t , -\cos t, 0)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=t\cos t\,\hi-t\sin t\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
|\vL'(t)|&amp;=\sqrt{t^2\cos^2 t + t^2\sin t^2  }=|t|
</mrow>
</md>
</li>
</ul>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2002A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
 Consider the space curve <m>\Gamma</m> whose vector equation is
<me>
\vr(t)=t\sin(\pi t)\,\hi+t\cos(\pi t)\,\hj +t^2\hk\,\qquad 0\le t \lt \infty
</me>
This curve starts from the origin and eventually reaches the ellipsoid
<m>E</m> whose equation is <m>2x^2+2y^2+z^2=24</m>.
<ol label="a">
<li>
Determine the coordinates of the point <m>P</m> where <m>\Gamma</m> intersects <m>E</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the tangent vector of <m>\Gamma</m> at the point <m>P</m>.
</li>
<li>
Does <m>\Gamma</m> intersect <m>E</m> at right angles? Why or why not?
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\vr(2)=2\hj+4\hk</m>
</p><p>
(b) any nonzero multiple of <m>\vr'(2)=2\pi\,\hi+\hj+4\,\hk</m>
</p>

<p>(c) <m>\Gamma</m> and <m>E</m> do not intersect at right angles.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) The curve intersects <m>E</m> when
<md>
<mrow>
2\big(t\sin(\pi t)\big)^2+2\big(t\cos(\pi t)\big)^2 +\big(t^2\big)^2=24
&amp;\iff 2t^2+t^4=24
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\iff (t^2-4)(t^2+6)=0
</mrow>
</md>
Since we need <m>t \gt 0</m>, the desired time is <m>t=2</m> and the corresponding point
is <m>\vr(2)=2\,\hj+4\,\hk</m>.
</p>

<p>(b) Since
<me>
\vr'(t)=\big[\sin(\pi t)+\pi t\cos(\pi t)\big]\hi
    +\big[\cos(\pi t)-\pi t\sin(\pi t)\big]\hj + 2t\hk
</me>
a tangent vector to <m>\Gamma</m> at <m>P</m> is any nonzero multiple of
<me>
\vr'(2)=2\pi\,\hi+\hj+4\,\hk
</me>
</p>

<p>(c) A normal vector to <m>E</m> at <m>P</m> is
<me>
\vnabla(2x^2+2y^2+z^2)\big|_{(0,2,4)}= \llt 4x,4y,2z\rgt\big|_{(0,2,4)}
=\llt 0,8,8\rgt
</me>
Since <m>\vr'(2)</m> and <m>\llt 0,8,8\rgt</m> are not parallel, <m>\Gamma</m> and <m>E</m>
do not intersect at right angles.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2001A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Suppose a particle in 3-dimensional space travels with
position vector <m>\vr(t)</m>, which satisfies <m>\vr'(t)=-\vr(t)</m>. Show
that the <q>energy</q> <m>|\vr(t)|^2+|\vr'(t)|^2</m> is constant (that is,
independent of <m>t</m>).
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>\diff{}{t}\big[|\vr(t)|^2+|\vr'(t)|^2\big]=0</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
<md>
<mrow>
\diff{}{t}\big[|\vr(t)|^2+|\vr'(t)|^2\big]
&amp;=\diff{}{t}\big[\vr(t)\cdot\vr(t)+\vr'(t)\cdot\vr'(t)\big]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\vr(t)\cdot\vr'(t)+2\vr'(t)\cdot\vr'(t)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\vr'(t)\cdot\big[\vr(t)+\vr'(t)\big]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=0\qquad \text{ since } \vr'(t)=-\vr(t)
</mrow>
</md>
Since <m>\diff{}{t}\big[|\vr(t)|^2+|\vr'(t)|^2\big]=0</m> for all
<m>t</m>, <m>|\vr(t)|^2+|\vr'(t)|^2</m> is independent of <m>t</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>

